<<<explanation>>>: The problem is that you are writing string without a line break. But BufferedReader expects one of the line characters mentioned above which you are not providing. It does output the whole buffer once the end of the stream is reached though.

A: The problem is that you are writing strings without a line break. BufferedReader expects one of the line characters (like \n, \r, \r\n) to indicate the end of a line. You are not providing this, so BufferedReader reads all the data you write and prints it as a single string.
You can solve this by adding a line break after each string you write:
printWriter.write("1\n");
printWriter.write("2\n");
printWriter.write("3\n");

This tells BufferedReader that each string ends with a line break, so it can separate them correctly.

A: You need to flush the PrintWriter after each write operation.
printWriter.write("1");
printWriter.flush();
printWriter.write("2");
printWriter.flush();
printWriter.write("3");
printWriter.flush();

Without flushing, the PrintWriter might not send the data immediately to the other side.

